data.content:
Yes! MSTest 3.7+ supports **ValueTuple** return types for `DynamicData`, eliminating the `object[]` casts:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- Return type: `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>`
- Data entries: `["...", true]` → `("...", true)`

The test method signature stays the same — MSTest destructures the tuple into the method parameters automatically. You get compile-time type checking on your test data now, so a typo like `("valid@email.com", "true")` would fail to build instead of failing at runtime.
